162
00:13:09,805 --> 00:13:17,029
teens at 83 percent. In comparison, those who self-identified as white were 71 percent likely

163
00:13:17,029 --> 00:13:20,991
to play video games and Hispanic teens were 69 percent.

164
00:13:23,470 --> 00:13:29,695
Take that in comparison to the IGDA statistic that basically says that less than 2% of all

165
00:13:29,695 --> 00:13:36,640
game makers identify as black. That's a huge disparity and it's the thing I felt as a kid

166
00:13:36,640 --> 00:13:41,063
and continue to feel as some of the other game designers and developers have mentioned.

167
00:13:41,063 --> 00:13:44,366
Basically if 90% of my childhood friends owned or played a console game,

168
00:13:44,797 --> 00:13:48,381
I was the only one actually making games.

169
00:13:48,381 --> 00:13:54,647
And so there's this real sense of loneliness or sense of being different and outside of

170
00:13:54,647 --> 00:13:59,151
a community that you'll see persists in a lot of the observations.

171
00:13:59,151 --> 00:14:03,055
So my story in a lot of biographies, my story illustrates a common tale.

172
00:14:03,740 --> 00:14:08,984
And that common tale is basically that the community of black game makers is much larger,

173
00:14:08,984 --> 00:14:15,108
or game players, is much larger than the community of black game makers. There are far more black

174
00:14:15,108 --> 00:14:19,010
people playing games than there are in people of the African-American diaspora and the African

175
00:14:19,010 --> 00:14:24,113
diaspora. There are far more people playing, obviously, than there are in the community of

176
00:14:24,113 --> 00:14:30,918
black game makers. And it's not even a question of proportion. It's actually, it's disproportionate,

177
00:14:30,918 --> 00:14:32,198
exceptionally disproportionate.

178
00:14:32,378 --> 00:14:37,080
even when compared to any other population. So I want to share with you some Black Game Maker

