211
00:17:01,112 --> 00:17:11,037
and then basically creating a game around whatever sort of product comes from a participatory or co-design approach.

212
00:17:11,037 --> 00:17:15,839
And then you have other folks who are doing things around indigenous economic justice.

213
00:17:15,839 --> 00:17:18,360
So this is EarthCypher from MediaBreeze.

214
00:17:19,265 --> 00:17:22,126
And you also have this other theme of fostering community.

215
00:17:22,126 --> 00:17:25,287
There was a lot of discussion from people who were making these games

216
00:17:25,287 --> 00:17:28,008
talking about how they want to foster community.

217
00:17:28,008 --> 00:17:31,450
So Spill It is an interesting one, and I like some of the artwork from their website.

218
00:17:31,450 --> 00:17:36,812
These photographs you see on the left, they'll have a persistent appearance

219
00:17:36,812 --> 00:17:40,313
because I shot them myself after I played the games.

220
00:17:40,313 --> 00:17:45,355
But in short, they're sort of talking about the opportunity to let Spill It spice up your kickbacks.

221
00:17:47,032 --> 00:17:52,056
and help you understand sort of like getting a little more casual with folks.

222
00:17:52,056 --> 00:17:56,399
But there's a whole other space where other people are creating games for

223
00:17:56,399 --> 00:17:58,941
Black people by Black people. It's sort of the

224
00:17:58,941 --> 00:18:03,144
by Black movement. And for some, being a Black game maker

225
00:18:03,144 --> 00:18:08,048
is central to the design itself. And for others, identity isn't actually

226
00:18:08,048 --> 00:18:12,371
central. And I want to emphasize that not every Black game is about Black

227
00:18:12,371 --> 00:18:12,952
identity.

228
00:18:13,810 --> 00:18:20,734
So almost everyone noted that there is an expectation of making what folks would expect is a black game.

229
00:18:20,734 --> 00:18:27,417
And so it's important to recognize, and people had mentioned this, recognize the diaspora,

230
00:18:27,417 --> 00:18:33,681
that African-American is quite diverse and that there are a lot of different experiences

231
00:18:33,681 --> 00:18:37,903
and sense of what it means to be a member of the black community.

232
00:18:38,927 --> 00:18:45,273
So basically, being black doesn't require that the game actually incorporate what are

233
00:18:45,273 --> 00:18:49,777
kind of stereotypical black culture elements. It can still be a black game if it doesn't

234
00:18:49,777 --> 00:18:54,722
include hip hop. It can still be a black game if it doesn't include what other elements

235
00:18:54,722 --> 00:19:01,608
someone might assume make it black. And so, examples of this, things like Sky Temple Stack,

236
00:19:01,608 --> 00:19:05,812
a nice mobile game, quite pretty, are examples of that.

237
00:19:06,153 --> 00:19:12,317
As is Tiny Bird Garden. Here's Tiny Bird Garden Deluxe being shown.

238
00:19:12,317 --> 00:19:15,379
Really interesting game, very different.

239
00:19:15,379 --> 00:19:19,921
Or Museum Multiverse to make sure I show you at least a few VR games.

240
00:19:19,921 --> 00:19:27,026
Another VR game is basically Run, Die, Run Again, but it's a first-person parkour game.

241
00:19:27,026 --> 00:19:29,027
Another really beautiful game by Retro Ninja.

242
00:19:30,367 --> 00:19:37,613
And we've got other games on the independent side that focus on other

243
00:19:37,613 --> 00:19:41,977
themes that are related to social impact. So operator is basically about a

244
00:19:41,977 --> 00:19:45,501
journalist that has to use her police scanner to keep her sister out of harm's

245
00:19:45,501 --> 00:19:50,285
way while an intense protest becomes increasingly unsafe. You can see the URL

246
00:19:50,285 --> 00:19:54,289
there. I encourage you to play it, get that experience. And generally

247
00:19:55,501 --> 00:20:01,322
I want to help people understand that Black Games are as wide and diverse as the people that actually make them.

248
00:20:01,322 --> 00:20:05,863
And it seems so obvious to state this, it seems like I shouldn't need to state this,

249
00:20:05,863 --> 00:20:09,584
but in talking to people, especially folks who weren't familiar with Black Games,

250
00:20:09,584 --> 00:20:17,046
what I found is that this is a surprising observation and news to people, unfortunately.

251
00:20:17,046 --> 00:20:17,186
So...

252
00:20:18,045 --> 00:20:21,746
For example, black games include art themes.

253
00:20:21,746 --> 00:20:25,887
So this is Artifacts 2 by Fizzaro,

254
00:20:25,887 --> 00:20:28,708
which is self-described as a game

255
00:20:28,708 --> 00:20:31,829
about the entanglement of trauma in the mind and body.

256
00:20:31,829 --> 00:20:36,090
And this is an IndieCade finalist or IndieCade selection

257
00:20:36,090 --> 00:20:38,951
back in 2018, a really interesting game.

258
00:20:38,951 --> 00:20:40,371
Or religious themes.

259
00:20:40,371 --> 00:20:43,652
So When I Get Free is a Christian Bible-themed playable

260
00:20:43,652 --> 00:20:45,893
graphic novel that...

261
00:20:47,155 --> 00:20:51,498
I think illustrates how these things can be integrated into gameplay.

262
00:20:51,498 --> 00:20:56,902
And then we have a bunch of other games that are sort of new takes on old mechanics,

263
00:20:56,902 --> 00:20:59,023
as I've done these analyses.

264
00:20:59,023 --> 00:21:03,126
So Rageball, for example, I like its tagline.

265
00:21:03,126 --> 00:21:04,727
Anything else is just Pong.

266
00:21:04,727 --> 00:21:09,530
But you can see some familiar mechanics and then some changes there.

267
00:21:10,469 --> 00:21:16,654
Or I think you'd kind of be under a rock if you hadn't heard about Treachery and Beatdown City at this point.

268
00:21:16,654 --> 00:21:22,999
But, you know, really different set of experiences.

269
00:21:22,999 --> 00:21:30,805
Or Combat Corps is another game I think I'd reference here that I think is really interesting and available.

270
00:21:31,178 --> 00:21:36,840
And then there are even games that maybe not are just flirting with interesting new mechanics,

271
00:21:36,840 --> 00:21:42,941
but also just fundamentally distinct experiences that may, and I want to emphasize this,

272
00:21:42,941 --> 00:21:47,803
may incorporate themes of blackness, but not in the ways that we would, I think, people would

273
00:21:47,803 --> 00:21:53,845
expect. So it's not about saying, oh look, I have a person of color as my main character,

274
00:21:53,845 --> 00:21:59,486
but there are experiences like the entanglement of trauma that come through in really interesting

275
00:21:59,486 --> 00:21:59,847
ways.

276
00:22:00,496 --> 00:22:05,202
So, Hex Gambit's an interesting game I would encourage you to take a look at.

277
00:22:05,202 --> 00:22:09,047
As is Chrono Ghost, really sort of pretty platformer.

278
00:22:09,047 --> 00:22:14,794
Or, if you're looking for something really different, consider something like Galactic Bar Fight.

279
00:22:14,794 --> 00:22:17,458
Weird Kid Studios produced this.

280
00:22:18,854 --> 00:22:30,519
I just want to kind of wrap up with some closing thoughts and give some sense of sort of what's next and just kind of help you reflect on the situation of black games these days.

281
00:22:31,267 --> 00:22:35,388
So I really did start this project to document the game makers in their games.

282
00:22:35,388 --> 00:22:38,210
And I was really excited about doing that.

283
00:22:38,210 --> 00:22:43,272
And as I did it, I realized that it's really important to tell black stories and to

284
00:22:43,272 --> 00:22:46,413
recognize black cultural production in games.

285
00:22:46,413 --> 00:22:50,455
It's not just this sort of horrible history in the U.S.

286
00:22:50,455 --> 00:22:55,097
of really disrespecting the black community.

287
00:22:55,097 --> 00:22:59,679
It's also just about recognizing the contributions that may not always be

288
00:22:59,679 --> 00:23:00,219
amplified.

289
00:23:01,114 --> 00:23:05,976
So from those stories, I've learned some things that I think are really worth sharing.

290
00:23:05,976 --> 00:23:11,719
And one of them is this idea that in the absence of community, we build it ourselves. So there's a

291
00:23:11,719 --> 00:23:14,100
lot of activity around saying...

292
00:23:14,436 --> 00:23:16,577
It's really hard to get into the games industry.

293
00:23:16,577 --> 00:23:18,458
People aren't really supportive.

294
00:23:18,458 --> 00:23:20,498
It's really hard when you're the only person of color

295
00:23:20,498 --> 00:23:21,879
or the only person in the black community.

296
00:23:21,879 --> 00:23:25,020
And so a lot of people have made these efforts

297
00:23:25,020 --> 00:23:28,702
to create their own spaces, websites,

298
00:23:28,702 --> 00:23:30,042
Facebook groups, et cetera.

299
00:23:30,042 --> 00:23:32,363
So in the absence of community, we build it ourselves,

300
00:23:32,363 --> 00:23:34,384
seems to be a thing I've seen.

301
00:23:34,384 --> 00:23:37,305
Likewise, in the absence of access,

302
00:23:37,305 --> 00:23:39,186
you see people trying to create it.

303
00:23:39,186 --> 00:23:41,526
So creating training programs, creating support,

304
00:23:41,526 --> 00:23:43,347
creating social gatherings.

305
00:23:43,782 --> 00:23:51,469
And again, it would be great if that absence of access didn't exist, but that the positive note is that people are creating those spaces.

306
00:23:51,469 --> 00:23:53,130
And I think that's part of the future.

307
00:23:53,130 --> 00:24:01,538
And then in the absence of support, we support ourselves, which is another sort of theme that kept coming through as I saw who was succeeding and how they were succeeding.

308
00:24:03,445 --> 00:24:08,469
So I want to kind of remind people that games are actually part of a milieu of culture.

309
00:24:08,469 --> 00:24:14,973
There's a wide array of cultural contributions that games make.

310
00:24:14,973 --> 00:24:19,736
And so I strongly believe that games themselves, the games industry, the games practice, is

311
00:24:19,736 --> 00:24:25,901
healthiest not as a monoculture, not rows and rows of the same work by the same people,

312
00:24:25,901 --> 00:24:30,003
but instead as something that is born from diversity.

313
00:24:30,224 --> 00:24:40,433
So much like a natural monoculture versus a diverse environment, a diverse environment can weather storms and monoculture can create some really bad situations.

314
00:24:40,433 --> 00:24:46,238
So the game making community is stronger when it's diverse, in my humble opinion.

315
00:24:46,238 --> 00:24:54,186
So I'd strongly encourage all of us to work towards cultivating that diversity, to cultivate diversity across the spectrum.

316
00:24:55,049 --> 00:24:58,270
And of course, I have to remind you that Black Games matter,

317
00:24:58,270 --> 00:25:00,811
which is why I did this research and why

318
00:25:00,811 --> 00:25:03,051
I'm trying to share this work and put in front of you

319
00:25:03,051 --> 00:25:05,492
a variety of work that others have created.

320
00:25:05,492 --> 00:25:05,672
So thanks.

321
00:25:05,672 --> 00:25:10,614
You can shoot me an email if you have any questions,

322
00:25:10,614 --> 00:25:12,894
and I'll be happy to answer them.

323
00:25:12,894 --> 00:25:13,555
Have a great day.

